"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 13–14
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1samuel-13-14-fill.py

Historical/ANE/textual context:

Ch13: Saul's first major failure — unauthorized sacrifice at Gilgal; Samuel's
      rejection oracle; Iron Age I weapons shortage under Philistine monopoly.
Ch14: Jonathan's faith-solo at Michmash; divine panic; Saul's rash oath;
      blood-eating crisis; the lot falls on Jonathan; the crowd redeems him.

Key contextual issues:
- 13:1 — MT textual corruption: numeral missing from age formula
- 13:5 — "30,000 chariots" vs LXX/scholars' 3,000 (scribal dittography)
- 13:8 — The 1 Sam 10:8 appointment; Saul's waiting period
- 13:9-14 — Sacral order: only designated persons may offer sacrifice
- 13:19-22 — Iron Age I Philistine iron monopoly; archaeology confirms
- 14:3 — Ahijah from Eli's condemned line; ephod for divination
- 14:18 — "Bring the ark" vs LXX "bring the ephod"; text-critical problem
- 14:41 — LXX preserves fuller Urim/Thummim prayer not in MT
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The MT age formula is textually corrupt: <em>ben-šānāh šāʾûl bəmalekô</em> — literally &ldquo;a son of a year when he began to reign&rdquo; — makes no sense, since &ldquo;son of a year&rdquo; (i.e., one year old) would precede adult kingship. The numeral(s) have been lost in transmission; blank spaces or bracketed numbers appear in most critical texts. The NIV, ESV, and others bracket the missing number. Ancient versions (LXX, Syriac) show variant traditions but none resolves the difficulty with confidence. The parallel formula in 2 Sam 5:4 (&ldquo;David was thirty years old when he became king&rdquo;) shows what the original phrase should look like — a numeral followed by the reign length. Acts 13:21 supplies &ldquo;forty years&rdquo; for Saul&rsquo;s reign, which accords with Josephus (<em>Antiquities</em> 6.14.9), though this too is disputed. The textual damage is ancient and likely irrecoverable.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s three-part deployment reflects standard Iron Age I hill-country military strategy: holding key passes and high-ground positions rather than engaging on the coastal plain where Philistine chariot advantage would be decisive. Michmash (modern Mukhmas, ca. 11 km northeast of Jerusalem) commands the central Benjamin ridge road. Gibeah of Benjamin (Tel el-Ful) was Saul&rsquo;s own base. The initial force of 3,000 reflects a standing professional army distinct from the tribal muster (<em>ṣābāʾ</em>) — the Israelite transition from tribal militia to professional royal army that the monarchy was inaugurating. Sending &ldquo;the rest to their tents&rdquo; acknowledges that a standing national army could not yet be sustained.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The credit for the strike on the Philistine garrison at Geba is ambiguous: the text says Jonathan struck it, but Saul blew the trumpet and made the announcement. This is a pattern in the Saul-Jonathan narratives — Jonathan acts decisively, Saul claims or appropriates. The trumpet (<em>šôpār</em>) blast throughout the land was the standard alarm-muster signal (Judg 3:27; 6:34; Neh 4:20). The announcement &ldquo;let the Hebrews hear&rdquo; (<em>yišməʿû haʿibrîm</em>) uses the term &ldquo;Hebrews&rdquo; (<em>ʿibrîm</em>) rather than &ldquo;Israelites&rdquo; — a usage that may reflect how Philistines and other outsiders referred to them (cf. 14:11, 29:3; Gen 39:14). The Philistines&rsquo; declaration that &ldquo;Israel has become repugnant&rdquo; (<em>nibʾaš</em>, literally &ldquo;has caused a stench&rdquo;) is the idiom for declaring a relationship hostile and broken (cf. 2 Sam 10:6).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Gilgal (near Jericho, modern Tell es-Sultan area) was one of the most charged sites in Israel&rsquo;s memory: the first camp after crossing the Jordan (Josh 4:19-20), where circumcision was renewed (Josh 5:2-9) and Passover celebrated (Josh 5:10-12), and where Samuel had previously made Saul king before YHWH (11:14-15). Samuel&rsquo;s appointment in 10:8 — &ldquo;go down to Gilgal before me&rdquo; — gave Gilgal its significance as the designated meeting point. The people rallying there in fear created the pressure Saul would respond to with the unauthorized sacrifice. That Gilgal, the site of covenant renewal, becomes the site of Saul&rsquo;s first rejection is a deliberate geographic irony in the narrative.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;Thirty thousand chariots&rdquo; (<em>šelōšîm ʾelep rekeb</em>) has been disputed as a scribal error. Chariots were enormously expensive and logistically demanding; even Egypt and Assyria at their height fielded far fewer. Many scholars prefer the LXX reading or emend to 3,000, explaining the MT&rsquo;s 30,000 as dittography of a digit or a later hyperbolic expansion emphasizing Philistine overwhelming force. Israel&rsquo;s military situation — no swords or spears (v19-22) — was genuine enough that exaggeration was not needed; the 3,000 reading fits better with the narrative&rsquo;s subsequent account. The simile &ldquo;as numerous as the sand on the seashore&rdquo; (<em>kahōl ʾăšer ʿal-śəphat hayyām</em>) is a standard hyperbole of uncountable multitude used for enemies (Josh 11:4; Judg 7:12) and for Israel&rsquo;s promised descendants (Gen 22:17).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The hiding behavior — caves (<em>məʿārôt</em>), thickets (<em>ḥăḥîm</em>), rocks (<em>səlāʿîm</em>), cellars (<em>ṣəḥîḥîm</em>), cisterns (<em>bōrôt</em>) — accurately reflects the terrain of the Benjamin hill country, which is riddled with limestone caves and cisterns. Archaeological surveys in this region have documented hundreds of natural and cut rock chambers that served as storage, refuge, and dwelling. The word translated &ldquo;thickets&rdquo; (<em>ḥăḥîm</em>) is a hapax legomenon — appearing only here — and its precise meaning is debated; some read &ldquo;thorn bushes&rdquo; or &ldquo;crevices.&rdquo; The Shephelah region south of this area shows similar refuge use in later periods (the Bar Kokhba caves at Naḥal Ḥever preserved documents and skeletal remains of Jewish rebels hiding from Roman forces in 135 CE — the same terrain, the same survival logic).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Crossing the Jordan into Gilead was a traditional refuge from western threats: the Transjordanian territory offered terrain inaccessible to chariot-based forces and was outside the immediate Philistine sphere. The Jordan crossing functioned as both a physical and a symbolic boundary; those who remained with Saul at Gilgal are distinguished from those who fled — the trembling (<em>ḥărādîm</em>) of those remaining anticipates the divine trembling (<em>ḥărādāh</em>) that will shake the Philistine camp in 14:15. The same root connects Saul&rsquo;s cowering army with the divine panic YHWH will send — an irony the narrator exploits: Israel trembles before Philistines, then YHWH makes Philistines tremble before two men.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The &ldquo;seven days appointed by Samuel&rdquo; refers explicitly to 1 Sam 10:8, where Samuel commanded Saul: &ldquo;Go down before me to Gilgal, and I will come down to you to offer burnt offerings and sacrifice fellowship offerings. Wait seven days until I come to you and show you what to do.&rdquo; The command was given at the time of Saul&rsquo;s anointing and was a specific test of obedience. Ancient Near Eastern warfare had a sacral dimension: battles were preceded by consultation of the deity and sacrificial confirmation. At Gilgal, Samuel was the authoritative mediator of divine consultation. The pressure of deserting troops is real, but Saul&rsquo;s action — on the very last day of the waiting period — shows impatience that overrides the covenantal protocol.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The burnt offering (<em>ʿōlāh</em>) and fellowship offerings (<em>šəlāmîm</em>) were the two standard pre-battle sacrifices: the <em>ʿōlāh</em> (wholly consumed) consecrated the engagement to YHWH; the <em>šəlāmîm</em> (shared between altar, priest, and worshipper) expressed communal covenant fellowship before battle. The sacral restriction on who could offer these was well established by this period: only designated priests (Num 18:1-7; cf. 2 Chr 26:16-20, where Uzziah&rsquo;s attempt to offer incense is immediately punished with leprosy). Saul&rsquo;s motivation is understandable — his army is melting away, Samuel has not arrived, battle is imminent — but the action violates the institutional boundary between royal and priestly roles that the Mosaic legislation had carefully maintained.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The timing is precise and devastating: Samuel arrives the moment Saul finishes the offering. The narrative does not explain Samuel&rsquo;s delay — whether it was deliberate, providential, or circumstantial — but the narrative effect is to make Saul&rsquo;s impatience the sin, not merely the action. Had Saul waited even a moment longer, Samuel would have arrived in time. This literary precision is characteristic of the Deuteronomistic narrator&rsquo;s presentation of Israel&rsquo;s failures: the test is always designed to be passable if the person trusts. The Exodus parallel is instructive: Israel at Sinai (Exod 32) also faced a long wait (Moses was 40 days on the mountain) and also turned to unauthorized worship. The pattern — divine delay, human impatience, covenant breach — is a recurring narrative template.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s threefold explanation — the troops were deserting, Samuel had not come, the Philistines were massing — is a classic example of what the OT calls &ldquo;circumstances as excuse.&rdquo; Each element is factually true. The desertion was real (v7-8); Samuel was genuinely late; the Philistines had gathered (v5). But in the logic of covenant obedience, none of these facts absolves Saul. Samuel&rsquo;s question &ldquo;What have you done?&rdquo; (<em>māh ʿāśîtā</em>) is the same formula used to confront moral failures: to Adam (Gen 3:13), to Cain (Gen 4:10), to Abraham (Gen 12:18). The formula is not a request for information but an accusation that the answerer must self-incriminate before judgment is pronounced.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Saul says he &ldquo;felt forced to act&rdquo; (<em>wāʾetʾappaq wāʾaʿal hāʿōlāh</em>) — the verb <em>ʾāpaq</em> in the hitpael means to restrain oneself or, in its negative sense, to be unable to restrain oneself. Saul presents his action as compelled by circumstances. But the logic of covenant trust is precisely the rejection of situational compulsion as a valid override: the prophetic word (<em>dāḇar YHWH</em>) given through Samuel is not overridable by tactical calculation. The phrase &ldquo;I sought the favor of YHWH&rdquo; (<em>ḥillōtî et-pnê YHWH</em>) — literally &ldquo;I sweetened/smoothed the face of YHWH&rdquo; — is the standard idiom for pre-battle sacrifice (1 Kgs 13:6; Ps 119:58). Saul&rsquo;s theological vocabulary is correct; his method is unauthorized.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Samuel&rsquo;s verdict — &ldquo;you have acted foolishly&rdquo; (<em>niskaltā</em>) — uses the root <em>skl</em> in the niphal/hiphil, meaning to be foolish/act without understanding. This is a wisdom-tradition term for the person who acts without regard for the covenantal and moral order (Prov 17:20; Isa 44:25; Jer 10:8). Significantly, Samuel does not accuse Saul of malice but of failure of understanding — acting without recognizing the covenantal stakes of his action. The promised dynasty that would have been &ldquo;established forever&rdquo; (<em>hēkîn YHWH et-mamlakṯəkā ʿal-yiśrāʾēl ʿad-ʿôlām</em>) uses the language of the Davidic covenant that will be promised to David in 2 Sam 7:12-16. The conditional form here — &ldquo;if you had kept the commandment&rdquo; — implies that the permanent dynasty was available to Saul and forfeited.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;A man after his own heart&rdquo; (<em>ʾîš kəlibbô</em>) — the phrase <em>lēḇ</em> (heart) in ANE usage referred to the seat of will, intention, and understanding, not emotion in the modern sense. A person &ldquo;after YHWH&rsquo;s heart&rdquo; is one whose will aligns with YHWH&rsquo;s purposes — whose decision-making reflects covenant priorities rather than situational pressure. The phrase does not imply personal sinlessness (David&rsquo;s subsequent failures make that impossible) but structural alignment: the appointed king will seek what YHWH seeks. Paul cites this verse in Acts 13:22, combining it with Ps 89:20 (&ldquo;I have found David my servant&rdquo;) to make it programmatic for the entire Davidic theology. The LXX of v14 reads <em>kata tēn kardian autou</em> — kata marking conformity, not origin — which reinforces the alignment-of-will interpretation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>After delivering the oracle of rejection Samuel leaves — abruptly and without the ceremony of a formal farewell. The troop count of 600 (<em>keşeš-meʾôt ʾîš</em>) after the desertion recalls other pivotal moments in the HB where a similarly stripped-down force marked a new phase of YHWH&rsquo;s action: Gideon was reduced to 300 (Judg 7:7); the 600 at Gibeah (Judg 20:47); the 600 Danites (Judg 18:11). The number may reflect the minimum viable unit for a tribal military action rather than a precise census. &ldquo;Gibeah of Benjamin&rdquo; (Tell el-Ful, excavated by Albright in 1922 and 1933) showed Iron Age I remains consistent with a fortified hilltop military outpost, though the identification of the tower remains with Saul&rsquo;s citadel is not universally accepted.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The two forces are positioned for standoff: Saul and Jonathan at Gibeah of Benjamin (elevated, defensible), the Philistines at Michmash (controlling the north-central highlands road). The geography creates the dramatic contrast: Saul&rsquo;s depleted, sword-less force on the defensive hilltop while Philistine raiding parties range freely through the territory. The Michmash pass (Wadi Suweinit/Wadi al-Qelt headwaters) was the primary passage connecting the Jordan Valley to the Benjamin plateau — whoever controlled Michmash controlled movement between Jericho and Jerusalem. The narrative&rsquo;s description of Philistine raiding parties operating uncontested through Israelite territory is not merely background color but establishes the military and political humiliation that forms the context for Jonathan&rsquo;s act of faith in ch14.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The three Philistine raiding detachments (<em>rāʾš hammaḥăl</em> — literally &ldquo;the head/chief of the raiding party&rdquo;) fanned out on three roads that controlled the Benjamin hill country: north toward Ophrah (in the Shual region, exact location uncertain — possibly modern et-Taiyibeh); northwest toward Beth-horon (the strategic pass connecting the Shephelah to the central ridge, used in multiple military campaigns from Joshua through the Maccabees); and east toward the &ldquo;valley of Zeboim&rdquo; overlooking the wilderness (possibly the Wadi Farah or a ravine descending toward the Jordan rift). The three-directional deployment was a classic encirclement-and-terrorize strategy for establishing military dominance over a region without fixed battle.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Beth-horon (modern Beit &lsquo;Ur el-Foqa and Beit &lsquo;Ur et-Taḥta) was one of the most strategically significant passes in the entire land — the descent from the Judean-Benjaminite plateau to the Aijalon Valley and coastal plain. Joshua pursued Amorite kings down this pass (Josh 10:10-11); the Maccabees ambushed the Seleucid general Geron at Beth-horon (1 Macc 3:16-24). The Zeboim valley facing the wilderness — the Arabah desert to the east — formed the third axis of the Philistine raiding triangle. This three-directional control effectively encircled Saul&rsquo;s remaining force at Gibeah and made Israelite movement in any direction dangerous.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The iron monopoly is one of the most archaeologically corroborated facts in the entire Samuel narrative. Iron metallurgy spread through the Levant during the 12th–11th centuries BCE; the Philistines, with their Aegean connections and coastal trade networks, had access to iron technology that the interior hill-country population of early Israel largely lacked. Archaeological surveys of Iron Age I sites in the Shephelah and Benjamin highland have confirmed a sharp disparity in iron artifact distribution: coastal Philistine sites show iron tools and weapons, while sites in the central highlands show primarily bronze, copper, and flint. The Philistine policy of denying smithing services to Israelites (<em>kol-ḥāraš lōʾ yimmāṣēʾ bəkol-ʾereṣ yiśrāʾēl</em>) was an economic-military weapon: controlling metalworking technology controlled military capacity. Israel&rsquo;s inability to forge swords explains the astonishing detail of v22 — only Saul and Jonathan were armed.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Israelites&rsquo; dependence on Philistine smiths for agricultural implements shows that the monopoly was not merely military but economic. The plowshare (<em>ʾēt</em>), mattock (<em>maḥărēšāh</em>), axe (<em>qardom</em>), and sickle (<em>maḥărēšet</em>) were the core tools of subsistence agriculture; without them the Israelite population could not farm. This dependency made regular interaction with Philistine craftsmen unavoidable and gave the Philistines structural leverage over Israelite society beyond battlefield confrontation. The &ldquo;going down&rdquo; (<em>lāreded</em>) to the Philistines for sharpening reflects both the physical topography (Philistine workshops in the Shephelah and coastal plain were lower elevation) and the status asymmetry the narrator is emphasizing.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The pricing structure in v21 is notoriously difficult: the Hebrew <em>pîm</em> was unknown until 1907 when a pre-exilic weight inscribed <em>pîm</em> was discovered at Gezer, allowing scholars to identify it as approximately two-thirds of a shekel. This is one of the rare cases where an archaeological find directly clarified a difficult biblical text. The Gezer weight (and subsequently many similar inscribed weights) confirmed that the Israelites used a standardized weight system for commercial transactions. The pricing here — two-thirds of a shekel for larger implements, one-third for smaller ones — represents a significant economic imposition, since agricultural tools were essential for survival and their maintenance was unavoidable.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The resulting military situation is stated baldly: on the day of battle, the entire Israelite force except Saul and Jonathan themselves lacked swords or spears. This is the culmination of the iron monopoly narrative: the Philistines had so thoroughly controlled weapons technology that Israel&rsquo;s army was effectively disarmed. The detail explains both the initial Israelite flight (ch13:6-7) and the subsequent reliance on YHWH&rsquo;s direct intervention — there was simply no other way for an unarmed force to defeat iron-equipped Philistines except divine action. The same theological logic operates as in Gideon&rsquo;s reduction: human military incapacity becomes the space where YHWH demonstrates his power. Jonathan&rsquo;s attack in ch14, armed with only a sword against a garrison of trained Philistine soldiers, is all the more remarkable for this background.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Philistine garrison stationed at the Michmash pass (<em>maʿăbār mikəmāš</em>) was the strategic control point for movement between the Jordan rift valley and the central Benjamin plateau. The Wadi Suweinit cuts a dramatic gorge through the limestone at precisely this point; the two crags named in 14:4-5 (Bozez and Seneh) frame the narrow pass. The garrison&rsquo;s role was to hold this choke point — preventing Israelite resupply and communication while maintaining Philistine freedom of movement. Military surveyors as late as the 19th century (including Charles Wilson and Claude Conder of the Palestine Exploration Fund) described the Michmash pass as virtually impassable in strength — a small defending force could hold it against much larger attackers — which makes Jonathan&rsquo;s flanking assault in ch14 tactically brilliant as well as theologically bold.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s initiative is conspicuously independent: he does not tell his father (<em>wəlōʾ higgîd ləʾābîw</em>). Throughout the Saul narratives, Jonathan consistently acts while Saul consults, waits, or vacillates. The armor-bearer (<em>nōśēʾ kēlāyw</em>) — the junior warrior who carried weapons and finished off fallen enemies — was a standard fixture of ANE military practice; his role was both practical and honor-related (to leave an enemy alive after a battle wounded them was shameful). The relationship between a warrior and his armor-bearer was one of the closest in ancient military culture, involving absolute loyalty and personal risk-sharing. Jonathan&rsquo;s armor-bearer&rsquo;s response in v7 (&ldquo;I am with you — whatever you decide&rdquo;) is a model of that devotion.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s position under the pomegranate tree (<em>rimmôn</em>) at Migron presents a striking contrast to his son&rsquo;s active initiative. Pomegranate trees were associated with settled, cultivated land — the tree of peace and plenty rather than war. Migron (possibly Tel Umm Ali near Michmash) was on the edge of Gibeah — Saul was not advancing but holding position. The six hundred men with Saul (same count as 13:15) represent the entire available Israelite fighting force. That this is the full extent of the national army — huddled under a fruit tree while Philistines range freely — is the narrative&rsquo;s pointed statement of Saul&rsquo;s ineffectual kingship. Isaiah 10:28 mentions Migron in the Assyrian march on Jerusalem, confirming the site&rsquo;s military significance on the Benjamin road.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Ahijah&rsquo;s genealogy is inserted with careful precision: he is son of Ahitub, brother of Ichabod, son of Phinehas, son of Eli. This places him squarely in the line that Samuel&rsquo;s oracle (2:27-36) had condemned — the descendants of Eli who would be cut off from the priesthood. Ichabod (&ldquo;no glory&rdquo; or &ldquo;the glory has departed&rdquo;) was named at the death of Phinehas and the capture of the ark (4:21), making him the living embodiment of Shiloh&rsquo;s fall. That a priest from the condemned Elide line is functioning as Saul&rsquo;s chaplain-diviner is quietly ominous: Israel&rsquo;s king is served by a priesthood under divine judgment. The ephod (<em>ʾēpôd</em>) worn by Ahijah was the high priest&rsquo;s vestment used for divination — specifically for operating the Urim and Thummim (Exod 28:15-30). No one in camp knew Jonathan had gone — Saul is uninformed about his own son&rsquo;s movements.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The two crags Bozez (&ldquo;shining/white&rdquo; from root <em>bāṣaṣ</em>) and Seneh (&ldquo;thorny/acacia&rdquo;) frame the narrow pass of Michmash. Bozez on the north-facing side would receive less sun and thus gleam with moisture; Seneh on the south-facing side would be hotter and drier, characteristic of thorny scrub vegetation. The PEF surveys of the 19th century located two limestone crags in the Wadi Suweinit gorge matching these descriptions, and Charles Warren in 1868 identified the site with considerable confidence. The word <em>ḥammassaḥ</em> for &ldquo;pass&rdquo; refers to the crossing point between the two crags — an almost vertical rock face that Jonathan would have had to scale. The geographical precision of vv4-5 is consistent with early, local knowledge of the terrain.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The directional specification — northern crag facing Michmash, southern facing Gibeah — confirms the narrator&rsquo;s familiarity with the specific geography. Michmash was on the northern plateau above the wadi; Gibeah to the south. Between them the gorge drops some 150-200 meters in the Wadi Suweinit, creating the dramatic ravine that made the Philistine position virtually impregnable by conventional assault. The garrison would have expected any Israelite attack to come from the south (from Gibeah, where Saul&rsquo;s force was) — Jonathan&rsquo;s approach from below and through the rock face was both unexpected and tactically unexpected. The two facing crags also function as the &ldquo;gates&rdquo; of the sign system Jonathan proposes in vv8-10: their dialogue with the garrison would take place across this narrow divide.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s declaration — &ldquo;nothing prevents the LORD from saving by many or by few&rdquo; (<em>ʾên la-YHWH māṣôr lᵉhôšîaʿ bərab ʾô biməʿaṭ</em>) — is a concentrated statement of holy-war theology. The <em>māṣôr</em> (hindrance, restraint) is precisely what Israel&rsquo;s lack of weapons, their small numbers, and their unsupported position would appear to be. Jonathan&rsquo;s statement rejects numerical/material calculation as relevant to divine action. The term &ldquo;uncircumcised&rdquo; (<em>ʿārēlîm</em>) for the Philistines was the standard Israelite epithet expressing both the physical mark of covenant-exclusion (Philistines never practiced circumcision) and the theological implication: those without covenant standing stand outside YHWH&rsquo;s protection. The double term &ldquo;perhaps YHWH will act on our behalf&rdquo; (<em>ʾûlay yaʿăśeh YHWH lānû</em>) is not uncertainty but the proper epistemic humility before divine action — Jonathan cannot command YHWH, only act in faith and see.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The armor-bearer&rsquo;s response — &ldquo;whatever is in your heart, I am with you&rdquo; (<em>ʿăśeh kol-ʾăšer bəlibbəkā nəṭêh-lāk hinᵉnî ʿimmāk kilibbəkā</em>) — is an expression of the armor-bearer relationship at its ideal. The phrase &ldquo;as your heart, so my heart&rdquo; (<em>kilibbəkā</em>) is the language of covenantal identity: the armor-bearer&rsquo;s will is entirely subordinated to his principal&rsquo;s. Jehonadab the son of Rechab uses similar language to Jehu in 2 Kgs 10:15 (&ldquo;Is your heart right as my heart is with your heart?&rdquo;). The unconditional commitment described here — going into a virtually suicidal situation on the basis of another&rsquo;s word and trust in YHWH — is presented as a model of loyal action. Jonathan&rsquo;s leadership elicits this quality; Saul&rsquo;s commands, by contrast, produce trembling compliance (v52).</p>",
    "8": "<p>Jonathan proposes a binary test based on the enemy&rsquo;s speech — a form of omen-reading that converts the enemy&rsquo;s own response into a divine indicator. This is structurally similar to the confirmatory signs in the patriarchal narratives: Abraham&rsquo;s servant sought a sign from Rebekah&rsquo;s speech (Gen 24:14); Gideon&rsquo;s fleece-test (Judg 6:36-40) similarly sought divine confirmation through a natural sign. The sign Jonathan proposes is elegant in its logic: if the Philistines invite them up (&ldquo;come to us&rdquo;), they have broken their defensive position — a military posture expressing contempt rather than alarm. The Philistines would only say &ldquo;come up&rdquo; if they felt entirely confident; that confidence would itself be the evidence of YHWH&rsquo;s action in blinding them to the danger.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;Stay there until we come to you&rdquo; would be the response of a force that recognized the threat and planned to descend and engage — a defensive posture that acknowledged Israelite danger. Jonathan&rsquo;s sign system reads the enemy&rsquo;s tactical response as a theological indicator: how the Philistines respond to being seen will reveal whether YHWH has set them up for defeat. This is a sophisticated understanding of how divine action works through natural and human events — YHWH does not typically intervene by halting suns or parting seas in every engagement; more often divine action is mediated through the clouded judgment, the misread terrain, the misplaced confidence of the enemy.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The sign activates on the word &ldquo;come up to us&rdquo; (<em>ʿălû ʾēlênû</em>) — a phrase of contemptuous invitation rather than tactical engagement. Ancient military practice involved taunting the enemy before battle as a way of psyching up one&rsquo;s own force and demoralizing the opponent. That the garrison would taunt two visible Israelites with &ldquo;come up and we&rsquo;ll show you something&rdquo; (v12) reflects the contemptuous confidence of a well-positioned, armed garrison toward an apparently absurdly outnumbered attacker. Jonathan reads this contempt as the sign: it shows YHWH has delivered them — literally &ldquo;YHWH has given them into Israel&rsquo;s hand&rdquo; (<em>nātan YHWH ʾôtām bəyad yiśrāʾēl</em>), the standard holy-war formula of divine donation (Deut 7:2; Josh 2:24).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Philistines&rsquo; exclamation — &ldquo;look, the Hebrews are coming out of the holes where they have been hiding&rdquo; — is contemptuous mockery: <em>ʿibrîm</em> (Hebrews) in Philistine usage is an ethnic slur denoting outsider/inferior status, and the reference to hiding holes picks up the hiding behavior described in 13:6. The Philistines see what they expect: cowardly Hebrews who had been hiding in caves now exposing themselves foolishly. Their contempt makes them incapable of evaluating the threat accurately — which is precisely the logic of the sign Jonathan proposed. YHWH&rsquo;s action often works through the hardened perception of the enemy, whose contempt becomes their vulnerability (cf. the hardening of Pharaoh&rsquo;s heart in Exodus).</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;Come on up — we&rsquo;ll show you something&rdquo; (<em>ʿălû ʾēlênû wənôdîʿāh ʾetkem dābār</em>) is exactly the sign Jonathan specified. The garrison&rsquo;s taunt — &ldquo;we&rsquo;ll let you know a thing or two&rdquo; — was standard military bravado, but in Jonathan&rsquo;s interpretive frame it is the activation of divine confirmation. Jonathan&rsquo;s immediate response — &ldquo;follow me; YHWH has given them into Israel&rsquo;s hand&rdquo; — shows no hesitation: the sign received, the action follows. The phrase &ldquo;YHWH has given&rdquo; (<em>nātan YHWH</em>) in the perfect tense presents the outcome as already accomplished even before the assault begins — the theological logic of holy war, where the divine donation precedes the human action.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The ascent &ldquo;on his hands and feet&rdquo; (<em>bəyādāyw ûbəraglāyw</em>) describes a technical rock-climbing maneuver up what was evidently a near-vertical limestone face — the east side of one of the two crags of the Michmash pass. The phrase is unique in the HB for combat: normal attack language uses &ldquo;coming up/against&rdquo; or &ldquo;striking.&rdquo; Jonathan&rsquo;s hands-and-feet ascent was not a charge but a climb, creating maximum tactical surprise. &ldquo;The Philistines fell before Jonathan&rdquo; (<em>wayyippəlû lipnê yəhônātān</em>) uses the standard formulaic phrase for divinely-aided military defeat; the armor-bearer&rsquo;s role was to ensure fallen enemies were definitively neutralized — the two men working in tandem, Jonathan knocking men down, the armor-bearer finishing them.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;About twenty men in a space of roughly half an acre&rdquo; — the Hebrew is difficult: <em>bəkeḥăṣî maʿănāh ṣemed śādeh</em> has been variously translated. The <em>maʿănāh</em> may refer to a furrow or the length of a plowing strip; the <em>ṣemed śādeh</em> (yoke of field) may be a land measure (approximately the area a yoke of oxen could plow in a day, roughly 0.5-1 acre). The twenty-man body count in a confined space would have been a scene of extreme tactical violence — Jonathan and his armor-bearer working methodically through a cramped garrison position. The precision of &ldquo;twenty men&rdquo; (<em>kəʿeśrîm ʾănāšîm</em>) alongside the vague area measurement suggests this detail derives from an early, specific source rather than later idealization.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The divine terror (<em>ḥărādāh gedôlāh</em> — great trembling) was the technical holy-war phenomenon: YHWH directly causes panic and confusion in the enemy force, overriding their normal military function. The HB has a specific vocabulary for this: <em>ḥěrēd</em>/<em>ḥărādāh</em> (terror-trembling, here and Josh 2:9), <em>māhûmāh</em> (divine panic, v20), <em>meḥûmāh</em> (confusion, Deut 7:23; 1 Sam 5:9). The shaking ground (<em>wayyirgaz hāʾāreṣ</em>) extended the panic from human to cosmic register: when YHWH acts in holy war, creation itself responds (cf. Ps 68:8; Judg 5:4-5). The terror spread from the garrison to the field army to the raiding parties — the entire Philistine deployment was affected simultaneously, which no human military action by two men could explain. The narrator identifies this explicitly as a divine act: <em>ḥărādāh ʾelōhîm</em> — &ldquo;a panic/terror of God.&rdquo;</p>",
    "16": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s sentries at Gibeah of Benjamin could observe the Michmash plateau from their elevated position. The phrase &ldquo;the Philistine mass disintegrating&rdquo; (<em>wayyimmōg hammaḥăneh wayyēlek wahălōm</em>) — literally &ldquo;the camp was melting away and going here and there&rdquo; — describes the visible breakdown of military formation. From Gibeah&rsquo;s vantage point (Tell el-Ful, ca. 895 meters elevation), the plateau of Michmash (ca. 640 meters, lower and visible to the north) would have been observable. The distance is approximately 3-4 km — near enough to observe troop movements but too far to understand their cause. This verse establishes that Saul&rsquo;s subsequent action (rallying his force, v20) was reactive to what the sentries reported rather than proactive based on his own intelligence.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The roll call (<em>piqūdû-nāʾ ûrəʾû mî hālak mimmennû</em> — &ldquo;call the roll and see who has gone from us&rdquo;) was standard pre-battle procedure: the force leader needed to know his strength before committing to action. The discovery that Jonathan and his armor-bearer were missing is presented as surprising — which confirms that Jonathan had slipped away covertly (v1 said no one knew) and that Saul had no intelligence about his own son&rsquo;s initiative. This verse amplifies Saul&rsquo;s passivity: while his army was collapsing, while his son was transforming the battle single-handedly, Saul was taking attendance.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The ark of God text (<em>hăgîšāh ʾărôn hāʾelōhîm</em>) is a significant textual problem. The MT reads &ldquo;bring the ark of God&rdquo; — but this is inconsistent with the ark&rsquo;s location: the ark was at Kiriath-jearim (7:2) since its return from the Philistines (ch6), not with the army. The LXX reads &ldquo;bring the ephod&rdquo; (<em>hăgîšāh tô ʾēpôd</em>), which is contextually coherent since (a) Ahijah is right there wearing the ephod (v3), (b) the ephod contained the Urim and Thummim for divination, and (c) v19 describes Saul then consulting through Ahijah and stopping the consultation — which fits ephod-divination, not ark-ceremony. Most text critics prefer the LXX reading here; the MT &ldquo;ark&rdquo; may reflect a later theological preference for the ark over the ephod or a scribal confusion of the two objects.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Saul interrupts the priestly consultation mid-process: &ldquo;withdraw your hand — stop&rdquo; (<em>ʾĕsōp yādəkā</em>). The &ldquo;hand&rdquo; refers to the priest&rsquo;s act of reaching into the pouch of the ephod to draw the Urim and Thummim lots. That Saul cuts off the oracle process before it is complete because &ldquo;the uproar in the Philistine camp grew louder&rdquo; shows the same pattern as his unauthorized sacrifice in ch13: circumstances override the divinely-appointed process. Both times Saul&rsquo;s military calculations trump covenant procedure. Here, however, the decision is strategically understandable — the Philistines were already routing and waiting for a lot-oracle would have wasted the moment. But the pattern of cutting off divine consultation persists: in ch28, when Saul can no longer get divine responses at all (v6), the earlier interruptions have had their cumulative effect.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The sword-against-comrade confusion (<em>ḥereḇ ʾîš bərēʿēhû</em> — &ldquo;the sword of each man against his companion&rdquo;) is the divine panic made concrete: troops in the confusion of holy-war panic turned on each other rather than on the enemy. The same phenomenon occurs at Gideon&rsquo;s night attack (Judg 7:22: &ldquo;YHWH set every man&rsquo;s sword against his companion&rdquo;) — the standard miraculous element of the divine-panic holy war. The archaeological and military record shows friendly-fire incidents in panicked retreats; the HB theology attributes the panic itself to divine action. Israel&rsquo;s role was simply to &ldquo;enter the battle&rdquo; (<em>wayyāqām śāʾûl wəkol-hāʿām ʾăšer ʾittô wayyāḇōʾû ʿad-hammilḥāmāh</em>) after YHWH had already done the work.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The &ldquo;Hebrews who had previously been serving with the Philistines&rdquo; (<em>haʿibrîm hāyû lappiləštîm kəʾetmôl šilšôm</em>) represents one of the clearest descriptions of social collaboration-under-occupation in the HB: Israelites serving in Philistine military capacity, either as mercenaries, coerced laborers, or tribute-required auxiliaries. Their switching sides at the moment of Philistine retreat is presented as opportunistic rather than principled — they joined the winners. This pattern of social stratification — some Israelites accommodating Philistine power, others resisting — reflects the political complexity of the transition period between tribal confederation and monarchy. The mention of this group also explains the earlier Philistine intelligence advantage (they had Israelite informants) and the subsequent Israelite knowledge of Philistine terrain and tactics.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The Israelites who had been hiding in the Ephraim highlands (13:6-7) came out when the Philistine flight became apparent — the same &ldquo;hiders&rdquo; who had been driven to caves and cisterns by the initial Philistine advance now joined the pursuit. The verb <em>wayyidběqû</em> (&ldquo;they pursued closely/clung to&rdquo;) suggests hot pursuit rather than mopping-up. The picture of a population that had scattered and hidden now converging on the fleeing Philistines is a snapshot of the reversal-of-fortune dynamic that characterizes the holy-war narratives: YHWH acts through a small faith-action, and the result transforms the entire strategic situation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&ldquo;The LORD saved Israel that day&rdquo; (<em>wayyôšaʿ YHWH bayôm hahûʾ et-yiśrāʾēl</em>) is the holy-war salvation formula — the canonical statement that YHWH was the agent. The formula echoes Exod 14:30 (&ldquo;and the LORD saved Israel that day from the hand of the Egyptians&rdquo;, same structure) and Judg 2:16, 18 (YHWH raised up judges to save). The fighting swept to Beth-aven (near Bethel, east of Ai — the western boundary of Philistine-controlled territory in this region), indicating a substantial territorial recovery. From Michmash to Beth-aven represents a westward push that reversed the Philistine presence in the Benjamin highlands. The naming of Beth-aven rather than Bethel is notable: the name means &ldquo;house of wickedness/emptiness&rdquo; and may be a polemical substitution for the shrine site associated with Jeroboam&rsquo;s calf (Hos 4:15; 5:8; 10:5).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s oath — &ldquo;cursed be the man who eats food before evening&rdquo; (<em>ʾārûr hāʾîš ʾăšer-yōʾkal leḥem ʿad-hāʿereḇ</em>) — was a <em>ḥērem</em>-style binding curse, a sacred oath that created legal obligation with supernatural sanction. Pre-battle fasting was a known practice of sacred dedication (cf. Judg 20:26; Joel 2:12), but imposing it on an army already exhausted from battle and now pursuing over substantial terrain was tactically self-defeating. The phrase &ldquo;until I have taken vengeance on my enemies&rdquo; (<em>niqamtî mēʾōyəbay</em>) uses the first-person singular — significantly, Saul claims the vengeance as his own rather than YHWH&rsquo;s. The contrast with Jonathan&rsquo;s &ldquo;perhaps YHWH will act on our behalf&rdquo; (v6) is stark: Jonathan attributes the battle to YHWH; Saul&rsquo;s oath frames it as his personal vengeance. The &ldquo;people were exhausted&rdquo; (<em>wāyyiggaʿ hāʿām</em>) is the direct result.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The forest with honey dripping on the ground was likely a wooded area in the Benjamin highlands where honeybees had nested in rock crevices or tree hollows, with honeycomb overflow or &ldquo;bees&rsquo; honey&rdquo; (<em>dəḇaš yāʿar</em> — wild honey, as distinct from cultivated hive honey) seeping from cracks in the rock. Palestine was historically renowned for wild honey (the &ldquo;land flowing with milk and honey&rdquo; formula); bee-keeping and wild honey collection are documented in ANE texts and Egyptian papyri. Wild honey was a high-energy food, and an exhausted army marching over highland terrain would have found it a significant resource. That the entire army was compelled to walk past freely available food without eating — because of Saul&rsquo;s oath — captures the human cost of his impulsive prohibition.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The troops&rsquo; restraint — &ldquo;no one lifted his hand to his mouth because they feared the oath&rdquo; (<em>ûpāḥad hāʿām et-haššəḇûʿāh</em>) — shows that Saul&rsquo;s oath was genuinely binding on the people. Sacred oaths in ANE culture carried real force: the curse formula (<em>ʾārûr</em>) was believed to activate divine punishment against violators. The word <em>pāḥad</em> (feared/dreaded) for the oath itself is interesting — the same root used for the &ldquo;fear of Isaac&rdquo; (<em>paḥad yiṣḥāq</em>, Gen 31:42, 53) as a divine epithet. The troops&rsquo; fear of the oath is real and appropriate; the problem is that the oath itself was rash and counterproductive. The narrator does not criticize the troops for their obedience but implies the oath should never have been uttered.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s ignorance of the oath is stated explicitly: &ldquo;Jonathan had not heard his father put the troops under the oath&rdquo; (<em>wəyôhānātān lōʾ-šāmaʿ bəhaššəbîaʿ ʾābîw et-hāʿām</em>). His action — touching the tip of his staff to the honeycomb and eating — was therefore not oath-violation but rather acted as a narrative foil: an innocent person performs the act that the oath prohibits, without guilt. The phrase &ldquo;his eyes lit up&rdquo; (<em>wayyāʾōrū ʿênāyw</em>) — literally &ldquo;his eyes were enlightened/brightened&rdquo; — is the physiological effect of blood sugar restoration in a state of exhaustion and hypoglycemia. The same phrase with the same literal meaning appears in Ps 19:8 (&ldquo;the commandment of the LORD enlightens the eyes&rdquo;) and 1 Sam 14:29 in Jonathan&rsquo;s own commentary, where the echo is deliberately invoked.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The soldier&rsquo;s explanation to Jonathan reveals that information about the oath had not been universally communicated: Jonathan was on a separate mission when the oath was pronounced and had not been informed. The report includes the oath&rsquo;s formula and its effect: &ldquo;that is why the troops are exhausted&rdquo; (<em>wayyiggaʿ hāʿām</em>). This verse functions as the exposition for the reader as well — filling in the causal chain between Saul&rsquo;s oath and the army&rsquo;s desperate condition. The phrase &ldquo;your father bound the army under a strict oath&rdquo; (<em>haʿēd heʿîd ʾābîkā et-hāʿām bišśəḇûʿāh</em>) — &ldquo;solemnly charged&rdquo; uses the infinitive absolute for emphasis — indicates the oath was made with maximum sacral force, not casually.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s critique — &ldquo;my father has brought trouble on the land&rdquo; (<em>ʿāḵar ʾābî et-hāʾāreṣ</em>) — uses the verb <em>ʿāḵar</em> which means to trouble/disturb the community&rsquo;s shalom or welfare. The same root appears in Achan&rsquo;s story (<em>ʿākān</em> = &ldquo;troubler&rdquo;; Josh 7:25: &ldquo;why did you trouble us? YHWH will trouble you this day&rdquo;). Jonathan&rsquo;s &ldquo;see how my eyes are bright because I tasted a little of this honey&rdquo; is a direct experiential argument: the honey restored his capacity; Saul&rsquo;s oath was therefore physically counterproductive to the military mission YHWH was accomplishing. Jonathan&rsquo;s critique of his father is not disrespect but a statement of covenantal reasoning: an action that harms Israel&rsquo;s ability to carry out YHWH&rsquo;s salvation work is a form of troubling the land.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&ldquo;How much better if the troops had eaten freely from the plunder they found from their enemies&rdquo; — Jonathan&rsquo;s military analysis is correct. Plunder-eating after battle (or during pursuit) was standard ANE practice: the troops had a right to the food and livestock they captured, and eating provided the energy for sustained pursuit. The word <em>šālāl</em> (plunder/spoil) was the legitimate warriors&rsquo; portion of victory. Jonathan&rsquo;s point: the slaughter of Philistines (<em>ûmaggēpāh bapəlishtîm</em> — the blow against the Philistines) would have been much greater had the army not been physically depleted. Saul&rsquo;s oath thus directly reduced the military effectiveness of the very battle YHWH was winning. The subtext is clear: Saul&rsquo;s rash oath worked against YHWH&rsquo;s purposes.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The geographical range of the battle — Michmash to Aijalon — represents approximately 20-25 km of pursuit across rough highland terrain, a substantial distance for an already exhausted army. Aijalon (modern Yalo, in the Aijalon Valley at the edge of the Shephelah) was the traditional boundary between Benjaminite highlands and the coastal plain where Philistine chariot forces were effective. Pursuing the Philistines to Aijalon meant driving them out of the highland entirely. The phrase &ldquo;they were utterly exhausted&rdquo; (<em>wayyāyaʿ hāʿām məʾōd</em>) — very/extremely exhausted — is the culmination of the oath&rsquo;s physical toll. They had fought and marched from dawn to sundown on empty stomachs.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The blood-eating violation — slaughtering animals and eating &ldquo;with the blood&rdquo; (<em>ʿal-haddām</em>) — was a direct violation of the Noahic prohibition (Gen 9:4) and the Mosaic law (Lev 17:14; Deut 12:23-25). Draining the blood before eating was a requirement so fundamental that it predates the Mosaic legislation — it was embedded in the food laws given to Noah as the covenant of all humanity. The reason given in Leviticus is theological: the blood is the life (<em>nepeš</em>) of the creature, and life belongs to YHWH; consuming blood would be consuming life-force that belongs to the Creator. The exhausted troops, their restraint broken the moment sunset came and the oath expired, &ldquo;swooped on the plunder&rdquo; (<em>wayyāʿaś hāʿām ʾel-haššālāl</em>) in their hunger and slaughtered animals directly on the ground — without the proper blood-draining that required elevation (a hanging carcass or a slaughter-rack).</p>",
    "33": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s response — rolling a large stone as an improvised slaughtering block — was practical and immediate: the stone elevated the animal so blood could drain properly. The theological logic was that blood must reach the ground and be covered or flow freely rather than pooling inside the carcass. Slaughtering &ldquo;on the ground&rdquo; (<em>ʾel-hāʾāreṣ</em>) in the previous verse meant the animals were killed lying down, trapping blood in the meat. The improvised stone-altar/slaughter station allowed proper blood-drainage. Saul&rsquo;s diagnosis — &ldquo;you have been faithless&rdquo; (<em>bəgedtem</em>) — uses the covenant-breach vocabulary; <em>bāgad</em> describes treacherous violation of relationship, particularly covenant relationship. The word is also used for marital infidelity (Jer 3:20; Mal 2:14-16).</p>",
    "34": "<p>The command &ldquo;each bring your ox, your sheep&rdquo; for slaughter at the official location was Saul acting as cult-regulator — organizing the community&rsquo;s food preparation to conform to the blood-prohibition. The instruction &ldquo;do not sin against the LORD by eating blood&rdquo; (<em>ʾal-tišʾû bêYHWH lēʾkol ʿal-haddām</em>) explicitly frames the blood prohibition as a sin against YHWH rather than a mere dietary rule — the theological weight of the command is covenantal. The people&rsquo;s compliance that night, bringing their animals in orderly fashion for proper slaughter, shows that the crisis was resolved through Saul&rsquo;s intervention. This is one of the few moments in ch13-14 where Saul functions effectively as a leader — addressing a real covenant violation with a practical, authoritative solution.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The notice that this was the &ldquo;first altar Saul built to YHWH&rdquo; (<em>rēʾšît ʾăšer hēḥēl liḇnôt mizbēaḥ la-YHWH</em>) — with the implication that he built more subsequently — is the narrator&rsquo;s only record of Saul as altar-builder. The Deuteronomistic History generally marks kings&rsquo; relationship to YHWH through their cultic behavior. David, Solomon, and others are shown building altars, organizing worship, and constructing the temple. That Saul&rsquo;s first altar is noticed here — after a chapter in which he performed unauthorized sacrifice, after an oath that nearly cost his army its effectiveness — is a study in contrast: the gesture of worship comes after a series of failed covenant acts. The altar does not repair what the unauthorized sacrifice and rash oath damaged.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s proposal to pursue and finish the Philistines receives the priest&rsquo;s interjection: &ldquo;let us draw near to God here&rdquo; (<em>niqqerəḇāh hēnnāh ʾel-hāʾelōhîm</em>) — the technical term for cultic approach to the deity for oracle consultation. The priest&rsquo;s reminder that divine authorization should precede military action is theologically correct and represents the ideal procedure Saul had violated in ch13. That the priest rather than Saul proposes consultation is itself revealing: Saul&rsquo;s instinct is tactical (&ldquo;don&rsquo;t let a man escape&rdquo;); the priest&rsquo;s instinct is covenantal (&ldquo;consult YHWH first&rdquo;). The scene at the newly built altar is ironic: the altar Saul has just built becomes the site where divine silence is discovered.</p>",
    "37": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s silence — &ldquo;he did not answer him that day&rdquo; (<em>wəlōʾ ʿānāhû bayyôm hahûʾ</em>) — was the most serious possible response to a pre-battle oracle inquiry. Divine silence was not merely absence of guidance but an active sign of divine displeasure (cf. Ps 28:1; Ezek 20:3; Mic 3:7). In the context of the Urim/Thummim oracle system, no answer meant the mechanism was blocked by unresolved sin in the community. Saul&rsquo;s deduction — &ldquo;something has gone wrong today&rdquo; — is theologically correct even if his proposed remedy (identifying and punishing the guilty party) will implicate his own son. The silence is the narrative hinge between the battle victory and the Jonathan-crisis.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s summons of the leaders (<em>kol-pinnôt hāʿām</em> — &ldquo;all the chief men of the people&rdquo;; <em>pinnâ</em> = corner/pillar, so &ldquo;cornerstones of the people&rdquo; = leaders) for a communal investigation of the sin follows standard ANE procedures for dealing with covenant breach that had drawn divine displeasure. The Achan narrative (Josh 7) is the structural parallel: when Israel was defeated at Ai because of Achan&rsquo;s violation, YHWH directed Joshua to identify the guilty party through a lot-casting process that narrowed from tribe to clan to household to individual — the same process that will unfold in vv39-42 here. Saul&rsquo;s language — &ldquo;let us find out where the sin lies that blocked God&rsquo;s answer today&rdquo; — uses the vocabulary of legal investigation rather than confession.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s oath — &ldquo;as the LORD who delivers Israel lives, even if it lies with Jonathan my own son, he will certainly die&rdquo; — was a judicial oath designed to demonstrate impartiality: the king will not protect even his own son from the consequences of covenant violation. The divine epithet &ldquo;the deliverer of Israel&rdquo; (<em>môšîaʿ yiśrāʾēl</em>) — the one who saves — is the same root as <em>yēšûaʿ</em> (Joshua/Jesus); invoking YHWH as Deliverer while preparing to condemn the man through whom YHWH just delivered Israel is the chapter&rsquo;s deepest irony. &ldquo;Not one of the people answered him&rdquo; — the silence of the troops in response to Saul&rsquo;s oath is ominous: they know what Jonathan has done, they know what YHWH has done through him, and they are already preparing their intervention (v45).</p>",
    "40": "<p>The binary division — &ldquo;you stand on one side; Jonathan and I on the other&rdquo; — reflects the lot-casting procedure of elimination. The lots (likely the Urim and Thummim, or plain casting stones) would indicate which group bore the sin. The people&rsquo;s agreement (&ldquo;do as seems best to you&rdquo; — <em>ʿăśēh haṭṭôḇ bəʿênêkā</em>) is technically compliant but the phrase will recur in a more negative register: &ldquo;do what is good in his own eyes&rdquo; is the chaos-formula of Judges (17:6; 21:25). The people are allowing Saul to proceed while preparing to override the outcome if it falls on Jonathan — which they do in v45.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s prayer — &ldquo;LORD God of Israel, give a true decision&rdquo; (<em>hābāh tāmîm</em>) — is brief in the MT. The LXX (Septuagint) preserves a significantly longer reading: &ldquo;If this iniquity was in me or Jonathan my son, O LORD God of Israel, give Urim; but if it was in your people Israel, give Thummim.&rdquo; This expanded text directly names the Urim and Thummim and describes the binary decision process. Most textual critics consider the LXX reading original and the MT to have suffered haplography (accidental omission due to similar-looking text). The Urim (<em>ûrîm</em>) and Thummim (<em>tummîm</em>) were the oracular objects kept in the high priest&rsquo;s breastpiece (Exod 28:30; Lev 8:8) — their precise nature is unknown, but the lot-casting function is clear from Num 27:21 and 1 Sam 28:6. The outcome: the lot fell on Saul and Jonathan, clearing the people.</p>",
    "42": "<p>&ldquo;Cast between me and Jonathan&rdquo; — the second-round lot narrows from the Saul-Jonathan group to determine the individual. That the lot falls on Jonathan — who genuinely did not know about the oath and whose action was both innocent and providentially successful — creates the narrative&rsquo;s most acute theological tension: the sacred lot is pointing to a man who has done nothing wrong within his own knowledge and through whose act YHWH won a great victory. The lot-system was understood as infallible in determining divine judgment (Prov 16:33: &ldquo;The lot is cast into the lap, but its every decision is from the LORD&rdquo;). Yet the people&rsquo;s intervention in v45 implicitly challenges whether the lot correctly identifies guilt — or whether it correctly identified the <em>technical</em> breach of the oath while the community recognized that the moral framework was Saul&rsquo;s failure, not Jonathan&rsquo;s.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s response — &ldquo;I tasted a little honey with the tip of my staff. Here I am, ready to die&rdquo; (<em>hinənî ʾāmût</em>) — is the model of honest self-presentation under legal interrogation. He neither minimizes the act (&ldquo;just a taste&rdquo;) nor denies it. The phrase &ldquo;here I am&rdquo; (<em>hinnənî</em>) is the standard response of availability and readiness before God (Abraham, Gen 22:1; Isaiah, Isa 6:8). Jonathan&rsquo;s readiness to die shows he accepts the sacred framework even though the situation is unjust. His calmness in this moment contrasts sharply with Saul&rsquo;s agitation throughout the chapter — Jonathan consistently demonstrates the kind of faith-grounded composure that the narrator has been associating with true kingship material.</p>",
    "44": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s death sentence — &ldquo;may God punish me severely if you do not die&rdquo; (<em>kōh-yaʿăśeh ʾelōhîm wəkōh yôsîp kî môt tāmût yôhānātān</em>) — uses the standard self-imprecation formula (<em>kōh yaʿăśeh... wəkōh yôsîp</em>, &ldquo;thus may God do and more also&rdquo;) used for binding oaths in the HB (Ruth 1:17; 1 Sam 3:17; 2 Sam 3:9,35; 1 Kgs 2:23). The sentence is absolute and public: Saul has invoked divine punishment on himself if he does not execute Jonathan. His earlier oath in v39 (&ldquo;even if it is my son Jonathan, he will certainly die&rdquo;) and the death sentence here lock him into an impossible position — to show mercy would be to break his own oath, to execute Jonathan would be to kill the instrument of YHWH&rsquo;s salvation. The people resolve the dilemma for him.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The popular intervention — &ldquo;should Jonathan die — the one who brought this great deliverance to Israel?&rdquo; (<em>hayônātān yāmût ʾăšer ʿāśāh hayyəšûʿāh haggədôlāh hazzōʾt bəyiśrāʾēl</em>) — overturns the judicial outcome of the lot. The people&rsquo;s argument is not that the lot was wrong but that the theological context makes Saul&rsquo;s oath illegitimate: Jonathan acted with/for YHWH (<em>ʿim-hāʾelōhîm ʿāśāh hayyôm hazzeh</em> — &ldquo;he has worked with God this day&rdquo;), and to execute him for an unknowing technical breach of a rash oath would compound Saul&rsquo;s original error. The phrase <em>padāh ʾet-yôhānātān</em> — &ldquo;the people redeemed Jonathan&rdquo; — uses the technical redemption vocabulary (<em>pādāh</em>, ransom/redeem) that elsewhere describes YHWH&rsquo;s redemptive acts (Deut 7:8; 2 Sam 4:9). The people collectively act as YHWH&rsquo;s redemption agents, paying Jonathan&rsquo;s death-debt.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The pursuit is abandoned (<em>wayyaʿal śāʾûl mēʾaḥarê pəlishtîm</em>) after the Jonathan crisis resolves. The Philistines return to their territory unopposed — the great opportunity for a decisive blow has been squandered by Saul&rsquo;s rash oath, the blood-eating crisis, and the lengthy lot-casting process. The irony is complete: YHWH&rsquo;s miraculous victory at Michmash, accomplished through Jonathan&rsquo;s faith and divine panic, ends with Saul calling off the pursuit rather than consolidating the gain. The Philistine problem will persist throughout Saul&rsquo;s reign (v52) and into David&rsquo;s.</p>",
    "47": "<p>The summary of Saul&rsquo;s military campaigns shows that, whatever his covenantal failures, Saul was an effective warrior-king: Moab, Ammon, Edom, Zobah (an Aramaean kingdom north of Damascus), and the Philistines were all fought; &ldquo;wherever he turned, he prevailed&rdquo; (<em>ûlekol ʾăšer yippāneh yarširaʿ</em> — though this form is unusual; some read <em>yāšīaʿ</em> from the root &ldquo;to act wickedly,&rdquo; giving &ldquo;wherever he turned, he did wrong,&rdquo; a more ironic reading). The standard reading with <em>hiršîaʿ</em> or the textual emendation to <em>yāšīaʿ</em> (&ldquo;he saved/delivered&rdquo;) fits better contextually. Saul&rsquo;s campaigns against Moab, Ammon, and Edom confirm Transjordanian threats that David would subsequently consolidate (2 Sam 8). The list of enemies mirrors and anticipates the enemies David will subdue — Saul laid the groundwork militarily even as he failed covenantally.</p>",
    "48": "<p>The Amalekite campaign mentioned here (v48) is summarized in one verse but will be narrated in full in ch15 — the episode that triggers Saul&rsquo;s second and definitive rejection. The notice here that Saul &ldquo;struck the Amalekites and rescued Israel from those who plundered them&rdquo; (<em>wayyak ʾet-ʿămālēq wayyaṣṣēl et-yiśrāʾēl miyyad šōsēhû</em>) presents the campaign in positive terms, which makes the subsequent narrative of ch15 — where the same campaign becomes the occasion for Saul&rsquo;s rejection for incomplete obedience — all the more significant. The summary section (vv47-52) appears to be a Deuteronomistic summary formula similar to the regnal summaries in Kings, providing the outline of the reign before returning to specific episodes.</p>",
    "49": "<p>Saul&rsquo;s family list: sons Jonathan, Ishvi, and Malchishua; daughters Merab and Michal. The son named &ldquo;Ishvi&rdquo; here is not mentioned elsewhere by that name; some scholars identify him with Abinadab mentioned in 31:2 (who died with Jonathan and Malchishua at Gilboa) or with &ldquo;Eshbaal&rdquo; (Saul&rsquo;s fourth son, 1 Chr 8:33; 9:39, who became king after Saul&rsquo;s death as Ish-bosheth). The name changes (Eshbaal → Ish-bosheth) were common in the later tradition where <em>baʿal</em> (lord) — used as a divine title applied to YHWH in early Israel — was replaced with <em>bōšet</em> (shame) to eliminate the Baal-cult associations (cf. Mephibosheth = Merib-baal, 2 Sam 4:4 vs 1 Chr 8:34). Michal will become significant as David&rsquo;s wife and the daughter Saul uses to bind David (18:20-28).</p>",
    "50": "<p>Abner son of Ner as Saul&rsquo;s army commander (<em>śar ṣābāʾ</em>) is introduced here without narrative development; he will become a major figure in the post-Saul succession conflict (2 Sam 2-3). The kinship note — Ner is Saul&rsquo;s uncle — places Abner in the inner dynastic circle: he was Saul&rsquo;s cousin, giving his military command a family basis as well as a merit basis. In ANE royal administration, kinship and military command were typically intertwined; the king&rsquo;s <em>śar ṣābāʾ</em> needed to be someone whose loyalty was secured by family interest as well as professional obligation. Abner&rsquo;s continued loyalty to the house of Saul after Saul&rsquo;s death (supporting Ish-bosheth against David, 2 Sam 2:8-10) reflects this deep family commitment.</p>",
    "51": "<p>The additional genealogical note — Kish the father of Saul, Ner the father of Abner, both sons of Abiel — establishes that Saul and Abner were first cousins (sons of brothers from the same grandfather Abiel). Genealogical precision at this point serves to legitimize Abner&rsquo;s role: he was not a general appointed by merit alone but a member of the Saulide clan with inherited standing. The Benjaminite genealogies preserved here and in 1 Chr 8-9 reflect the kind of clan records that would have been maintained by tribal leadership. This brief verse is the kind of archival material that the Deuteronomistic compiler drew on from earlier sources — its dry, formulaic character is characteristic of official genealogical notation rather than narrative composition.</p>",
    "52": "<p>The chapter&rsquo;s closing summary — &ldquo;war with the Philistines was fierce throughout Saul&rsquo;s reign&rdquo; (<em>wattəhî hammilḥāmāh ḥăzāqāh ʿal-pəlishtîm kol yəmê šāʾûl</em>) — confirms that despite the Michmash victory, the Philistine problem was never definitively resolved under Saul. The great battle of ch14 was a tactical victory, not strategic. Saul&rsquo;s practice of recruiting &ldquo;any capable or courageous man&rdquo; (<em>kol-ʾîš gibbôr wəkol-ben-ḥayil</em>) reflects the professionalization of the army that the monarchy was building — a permanent force beyond the tribal militia. David himself will be recruited through exactly this process (16:18-21). The verse thus provides both a closing frame for chs 13-14 and a narrative bridge to the Goliath episode (ch17) where the Philistine problem will come to its most famous expression.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '1samuel')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1samuel', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'1 Samuel 13-14 mkt-context written ({total} verses).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
